<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1190,1323]" pageId="1">
<taxonomicName box="[151,246,1190,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Exochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,246,1190,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1">Exochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be recognized (
<bibRefCitation author="Gauld" box="[480,687,1190,1215]" pageId="1" refString="Gauld, I., Sithole, R., Gomes, J. U. &amp; Godoy, C. (2002) The Ichneumonidae of Costa Rica, 4. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 66, 1 - 768." type="journal article" year="2002">
Gauld 
<emphasis box="[558,615,1190,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1">et al.</emphasis>
, 
<number box="[629,687,1191,1215]" pageId="1" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) by an obtusely to acutely pointed projection extending upwards a little above bases of antennae, outer spur of mid tibia shorter than inner one, fore wing without an enclosed areolet, metasoma without longitudinal carinae on tergite II. This group is known to parasitize a wide range of microlepidopterous larvae in leaf rolls, but the hosts of almost all Neotropical species are unknown.
</paragraph>
